column18: "manot […] considered as expressing 'a set.' When more than one ten is expressed, fulu is used" (p.100)
Krämer (1919:331) assumes power numerals over 1000 to be influenced by Western languages

column17: Müller (1917:125f.): similar, but one power less
Eilers' list of numerals ends at 600
Carroll & Soulik (1973): same numerals (except for 10) up to 10^8
column18: C&S (1973: 465): madaangahulu for objects, hulu in enumeration & compounds only; H&J (1984:72): hulu/mada for 10
beyond 10^6, counting returns to 1 (iwuit) & continues recursively (Kayser 1993:68)
Vesper (1970) gives siŋaul for 10 (but no higher power numerals)
Bingham (1922:15) gives tebwina for 10 objects and teñaun for 10 people (or 100 coconuts [p.17])
for power numerals in specific counting systems, see Erdland (1906:204f.); analysis in Bender & Beller (subm.)

column17: Eilers (1934:461-463) reports similar, yet more complicated numerals (except for 10) up to 10^9
Eilers (1934:397) reports similar, yet more complicated numerals (except for 10), and up to 1000 only

column18: Girschner (1913:171) reports eṅoal for rapid counting and most objects, säk for living beings

column17: Quackenbush (1968:201-203) reports a pattern in line with Trukic (with 1000 = ngaraj)

column18: Fritz (1911:19) reports sél for 10,000 and äpingit for 100,000; both J&M (1991) and Fritz (1911) report eyáf for units of 10 coconuts

column17: unclear whether Krämer (1937)'s power numerals for 100,000 onwards apply also to Lamotrek, or only to Fais

column18: for power numerals in specific counting systems, see Alkire (1970:10-13); analysis in Bender & Beller (subm.)

column17: power numeral for 100,000 presumably as in Lamotrek
column18: Krämer mentions fishing as explanation for the high numerals on Lamotrek and Feis
Tetens & Kubary (1873:58 [130]) report sek (10), seboukith (100), sangrass (1000)
for power numerals in pair-wise counting, see Eilers (1935:380); analysis in Bender & Beller (subm.)

column17: Eilers also renders numerals reported by Pickering, Hale, and  Hellwig
